         tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 45)

Unsurprisingly, as the total hole par increases, so do the number of strokes. Also unsurprisingly, players who made the cut had fewer stokes per round. Total number of strokes was positively correlated with each strokes gained category and negatively correlated with final position. Only players that made the cut recieved a final position ranking. For players that made the cut, each category of strokes gained was negatively related to final position. Additionally, the strokes gained categories were uncorrelated with each other indicating that they are independence. For example, strokes gained putting was not related to strokes gained on the approach. So, if a golfer is struggling in one area, that may be independent from performance in other areas.

4b. Strokes gained predicting position

pga$playerid<-as.factor(pga$`player id`)
pga$tourid<-as.factor(pga$`tournament id`)

m1<- lmer(pos ~ sg_ott+sg_app+sg_arg+sg_putt+(1|playerid:tourid), data=pga)

After accounting for clustering within player and tournament, all categories of of strokes gained predicted final position in players that made the cut.
